WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.340 --> 00:00:03.090
FEMALE SPEAKER: Everybody
knows this woman

00:00:03.090 --> 00:00:06.196
has been nominated for an Oscar
for her work in "House of Sand

00:00:06.196 --> 00:00:09.290
and Fog" and the Emmy for
Best Supporting Actress

00:00:09.290 --> 00:00:10.460
for "House of Saddam."

00:00:10.460 --> 00:00:12.790
SHOHREH AGHDASHLOO:
House house, house.

00:00:12.790 --> 00:00:16.345
FEMALE SPEAKER: I wasn't going
to point that out, but you did.

00:00:16.345 --> 00:00:18.720
SHOHREH AGHDASHLOO: It carried
on for a couple of years--

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:21.930
house, house, house,
house lake, "Lake House,"

00:00:21.930 --> 00:00:26.880
"House of Sand and Fog," "House
of Saddam," "Horror House."

00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:31.450
And then I had an offer for
"Odd Life of Timothy Green,"

00:00:31.450 --> 00:00:36.290
Disney movie, I thought,
OK, no more houses.

00:00:36.290 --> 00:00:38.770
This one has nothing
to do with a house.

00:00:38.770 --> 00:00:42.090
By the time I got
closer to Disney,

00:00:42.090 --> 00:00:45.370
where I had a meeting with
this amazing producer,

00:00:45.370 --> 00:00:47.690
I thought, I have to find
out what her name is,

00:00:47.690 --> 00:00:50.340
because I just can't get in
and say, hi, how are you?

00:00:50.340 --> 00:00:55.090
So I looked at my
cell phone to find out

00:00:55.090 --> 00:00:57.890
what her name is, so when
I enter, I would say,

00:00:57.890 --> 00:00:59.520
hello, Mrs. So-and-so.

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:00.570
Guess what?

00:01:00.570 --> 00:01:03.879
Her family name was Housebrick.

00:01:03.879 --> 00:01:04.379
Oh my god.

00:01:04.379 --> 00:01:06.670
It had to be her family name.

00:01:06.670 --> 00:01:09.820
It's not the name of the movie,
nor the name of the director,

00:01:09.820 --> 00:01:13.220
but the producer's
family name, Housebrick.

00:01:13.220 --> 00:01:18.490
So I thought, I'm still stuck
with house, which is beautiful.

00:01:18.490 --> 00:01:22.760
Ask every immigrant,
every displaced person who

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:27.870
has left her home
country, has migrated,

00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:29.770
ask them what comes first?

00:01:29.770 --> 00:01:32.380
They all tell you, house.

00:01:32.380 --> 00:01:34.160
Maybe that's why.

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:36.080
This was the universe
trying to tell me

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:39.350
that you have a house
with us no matter what.

00:01:39.350 --> 00:01:39.930
Maybe.

00:01:39.930 --> 00:01:42.940
FEMALE SPEAKER: And now you have
all of Earth in "The Expanse."

00:01:42.940 --> 00:01:44.690
Please tell us about
how you got involved.

00:01:44.690 --> 00:01:46.273
SHOHREH AGHDASHLOO:
So heartbeats away

00:01:46.273 --> 00:01:49.210
from governing the world,
ladies and gentlemen.

00:01:49.210 --> 00:01:50.270
Help me through.

00:01:50.270 --> 00:01:51.530
Vote for me.

00:01:51.530 --> 00:01:54.760
I promise you, I would
save Earth for you.

00:01:54.760 --> 00:02:01.226
I would not allow Mars nor
Sirius, nor the Belters

00:02:01.226 --> 00:02:03.360
to come and take our resources.

00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:06.340
That's what my character,
Chrisjen Avasarala,

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:08.300
is afraid of, and
she has the right

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:11.990
to be afraid of, of Martians.

00:02:11.990 --> 00:02:16.700
All they want is to come to
Earth and take our resources.

00:02:16.700 --> 00:02:18.280
And we still have a lot.

00:02:18.280 --> 00:02:22.540
We have already colonized
Mars and the solar system.

00:02:22.540 --> 00:02:25.900
We have colonized Belters
with all due respect

00:02:25.900 --> 00:02:29.240
to the chief of the
Belters here today.

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:32.170
But we're still afraid of them.

00:02:32.170 --> 00:02:37.160
The core of the idea
of politics has not

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:44.250
changed, not even in 200 years,
where this TV series is set at.

00:02:44.250 --> 00:02:49.080
So in numerous interviews
that I watched,

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:53.000
you talked about how
when it was nonfiction,

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.130
you would learn about the person
that you were about to portray,

00:02:56.130 --> 00:02:58.885
and in fiction, you
would create a history.

00:02:58.885 --> 00:03:00.260
SHOHREH AGHDASHLOO:
From scratch.

00:03:00.260 --> 00:03:03.220
FEMALE SPEAKER: From scratch,
so for Chrisjen Avasarala,

00:03:03.220 --> 00:03:04.475
what did you do?

00:03:04.475 --> 00:03:06.350
SHOHREH AGHDASHLOO:
Chrisjen was really hard,

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:08.530
my first politician.

00:03:08.530 --> 00:03:11.170
I had done lots of
doctors and professors.

00:03:11.170 --> 00:03:13.270
And I still remember a
comedian friend of mine

00:03:13.270 --> 00:03:16.100
once told me, oh,
Mrs. Aghdashloo, you

00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:18.350
get to play all the
doctors and professors.

00:03:18.350 --> 00:03:22.360
And I said, believe me, Antony,
I'm dying to play a maid.

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:23.670
He goes, a maid?

00:03:23.670 --> 00:03:24.382
You?

00:03:24.382 --> 00:03:27.210
You come in with
that voice of yours.

00:03:27.210 --> 00:03:30.810
You say, Madam,
the tea is ready.

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:33.870
That tea must be poisoned,
or there is no reason

00:03:33.870 --> 00:03:37.160
I'm bringing you into this!

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:42.340
He put an end to
my life's dream.

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:42.940
Thank god.

00:03:42.940 --> 00:03:43.680
I got it.

00:03:43.680 --> 00:03:44.590
I got it last year.

00:03:44.590 --> 00:03:48.910
I portrayed a maid in a movie
called "Septembers of Shiraz,"

00:03:48.910 --> 00:03:53.100
based on the Iranian
writer's book

00:03:53.100 --> 00:03:56.840
called "Septembers of Shiraz,"
New York's best seller.

00:03:56.840 --> 00:03:59.550
Amazing, with Adrian
Brody and Salma Hayek.

00:03:59.550 --> 00:04:01.480
Finally, I portrayed a maid.

00:04:01.480 --> 00:04:04.230
But a politician, it
was my first time.

00:04:04.230 --> 00:04:09.270
And I was, again, walking,
pacing, back and forth,

00:04:09.270 --> 00:04:12.610
thinking, how am
I going to create

00:04:12.610 --> 00:04:14.380
this character from scratch?

00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:17.839
I'm going to have to
start with my heroes,

00:04:17.839 --> 00:04:22.050
with women whom I have admired
since childhood, with women

00:04:22.050 --> 00:04:27.760
whom I have looked up
to, followed their path,

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:32.250
and wanted to be them or
to do what they are doing.

00:04:32.250 --> 00:04:35.090
So all of a sudden,
Indira Gandhi came.

00:04:35.090 --> 00:04:39.620
It was like the door opened,
and Indira came in, and I said,

00:04:39.620 --> 00:04:42.160
oh, Indira, please do sit down.

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:45.890
Obviously, Indira was
followed by Benazir Bhutto,

00:04:45.890 --> 00:04:49.250
one of my favorites ever.

00:04:49.250 --> 00:04:53.886
I loved her so much that I was
so furious when she was killed.

00:04:53.886 --> 00:04:55.510
I was furious with her.

00:04:55.510 --> 00:04:59.530
Why an educated woman,
a well-read politician,

00:04:59.530 --> 00:05:03.270
why she should poke out her
head from a limousine that

00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:08.642
is driving 5 miles per hour,
every assassin's paradise.

00:05:08.642 --> 00:05:11.160
Anyhow, Benazir came in,
and I'm looking at Benazir.

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:15.980
I'm like, although this
character is from far east,

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:20.190
far, far, far east, and it's
an international, universal

00:05:20.190 --> 00:05:24.790
character, but I still need
more women, more people,

00:05:24.790 --> 00:05:28.070
who are not necessarily
from east or far east.

00:05:28.070 --> 00:05:31.940
And obviously the door opens,
and another favorite of mine,

00:05:31.940 --> 00:05:34.210
Margaret Thatcher, comes in.

00:05:34.210 --> 00:05:36.280
I loved Thatcher.

00:05:36.280 --> 00:05:40.740
I happened to be in London when
she became a prime minister.

00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:45.170
Her first speech
changed my life forever.

00:05:45.170 --> 00:05:48.980
I wanted to study art
before I saw her speech.

00:05:48.980 --> 00:05:51.960
But right after her speech,
I decided to study politics.

00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:54.300
And I managed to do
it, and got my BA

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:58.160
in international relations,
political science in '84.

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:00.220
So Thatcher is coming.

00:06:00.220 --> 00:06:02.130
And I know in the
UK, it's very hard.

00:06:02.130 --> 00:06:04.110
When you say you love
Thatcher, some people

00:06:04.110 --> 00:06:06.940
really get upset with you.

00:06:06.940 --> 00:06:08.260
They're like how?

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:08.960
Why?

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:09.700
A woman like you?

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:12.300
And I said, well,
look, I was living here

00:06:12.300 --> 00:06:13.850
at the time of Callaghan.

00:06:13.850 --> 00:06:18.290
It was the Labour Party, and the
UK was on the verge of a nasty

00:06:18.290 --> 00:06:19.660
breakdown.

00:06:19.660 --> 00:06:20.630
Thatcher came.

00:06:20.630 --> 00:06:23.850
She said it in her speech.

00:06:23.850 --> 00:06:29.170
She said, I'm hearing rumors
that people call me Iron Lady.

00:06:29.170 --> 00:06:31.000
I am the Iron Lady.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:32.260
Tighten your belts.

00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:34.720
We are going to change
Britain for good.

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:36.430
And she did.

00:06:36.430 --> 00:06:39.470
So that's why I
love her so much.

00:06:39.470 --> 00:06:41.560
Right after her,
Madeleine Albright,

00:06:41.560 --> 00:06:45.120
another one of my heroes,
whom I love and adore.

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:53.260
Thatcher was followed by
Madeleine for a reason.

00:06:53.260 --> 00:06:56.100
Everything is interrelated
in this world.

00:06:56.100 --> 00:06:59.360
Both women are famous
for their broaches.

00:06:59.360 --> 00:07:02.180
They have books
about their broaches.

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:04.160
That's why Madeleine
followed Thatcher,

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:07.470
and right after that, of course,
Secretary Clinton, Hillary

00:07:07.470 --> 00:07:07.970
Clinton.

00:07:07.970 --> 00:07:11.050
And I'm like, OK,
now everybody's here.

00:07:11.050 --> 00:07:12.260
Now I can see them.

00:07:12.260 --> 00:07:13.470
I can feel them.

00:07:13.470 --> 00:07:15.090
It's so tangible now.

00:07:15.090 --> 00:07:16.770
I can see the character.

00:07:16.770 --> 00:07:20.760
Now I can start breathing
life into this character.

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:23.935
It was only then that I was
satisfied that I may be able.

00:07:23.935 --> 00:07:25.810
With all those, you were
two heartbeats away.

00:07:25.810 --> 00:07:26.976
SHOHREH AGHDASHLOO: Exactly.

00:07:26.976 --> 00:07:29.540
They were all there,
like "Sense8."

00:07:29.540 --> 00:07:31.430
All my other selves were there.

00:07:31.430 --> 00:07:32.920
Have you ever watched "Sense8"?

00:07:32.920 --> 00:07:33.420
FEMALE SPEAKER: Uh-huh.

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:34.878
SHOHREH AGHDASHLOO:
The Wachowskis.

00:07:34.878 --> 00:07:35.680
It's very nice.

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:39.431
I love that series, "Sense8."

00:07:39.431 --> 00:07:40.930
FEMALE SPEAKER: So
I have a question

00:07:40.930 --> 00:07:45.250
about what led you to
decide to write your memoir?

00:07:45.250 --> 00:07:47.310
SHOHREH AGHDASHLOO:
My American friends.

00:07:47.310 --> 00:07:47.510
FEMALE SPEAKER: Oh, really?

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:49.343
SHOHREH AGHDASHLOO:
More than anything else,

00:07:49.343 --> 00:07:50.750
my American friends.

00:07:50.750 --> 00:07:55.770
For 20 odd something years, I
was asked so many questions,

00:07:55.770 --> 00:08:00.400
so many odd questions about
driving camels back in Iran,

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:02.740
or about-- somebody
was actually like,

00:08:02.740 --> 00:08:04.550
did you have telephones in Iran?

00:08:04.550 --> 00:08:05.960
Like telephones?

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:09.270
Yes, we did have telephones.

00:08:09.270 --> 00:08:11.180
When I was born,
we had telephones.

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:14.460
So I thought, I have
to educate them.

00:08:14.460 --> 00:08:15.230
They have to know.

00:08:15.230 --> 00:08:18.830
We owe it to them, this
beautiful vast country

00:08:18.830 --> 00:08:23.230
who's been taking care of
us, who's been so graciously

00:08:23.230 --> 00:08:24.370
accepting us.

00:08:24.370 --> 00:08:27.640
So I thought, for the sake of
the people of this country,

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:30.770
for the sake of
the modern history,

00:08:30.770 --> 00:08:33.360
I need to write this down.

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:35.240
Another fact was
that every time I

00:08:35.240 --> 00:08:40.049
met an educated, well-read
American, elderly,

00:08:40.049 --> 00:08:43.150
immediately, they would
say, oh, you're from Iran.

00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:46.200
Yes, we do remember Iran,
what happened to Iran.

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:50.080
Mohammad Mosaddegh, the
first and last democratically

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:54.050
elected prime minister of Iran
who was sent to exile, CIA coup

00:08:54.050 --> 00:08:56.020
d'etat, 1953 in Iran.

00:08:56.020 --> 00:09:00.250
They knew every detail about
Mossadegh, this deposed

00:09:00.250 --> 00:09:02.140
prime minister of Iran.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:05.380
Young people, if I would
tell them that I was Iranian,

00:09:05.380 --> 00:09:08.290
they would say, oh,
Ahmadinejad, Ahmadinejad.

00:09:08.290 --> 00:09:11.590
And I just didn't want to be
identified with Ahmadinejad.

00:09:11.590 --> 00:09:15.560
I had to do something about it,
and I thought maybe the best

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:21.720
thing is to write my memoir,
but do not concentrate solely

00:09:21.720 --> 00:09:24.200
on the memoir,
because more or less,

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:25.740
we all have the same life.

00:09:25.740 --> 00:09:31.090
Every one of us is a
moving film, movies.

00:09:31.090 --> 00:09:37.390
But I can set my memoir against
the history, the modern history

00:09:37.390 --> 00:09:43.120
of Iran that was going on while
I was in Iran during the Shah's

00:09:43.120 --> 00:09:43.670
reign.

00:09:43.670 --> 00:09:48.950
Now that there's such a huge gap
that Americans know Mosaddegh,

00:09:48.950 --> 00:09:54.150
which was 52, and now they know
Ahmadinejad, which is 2008,

00:09:54.150 --> 00:09:58.950
as though Iran did not exist
in between the two of them.

00:09:58.950 --> 00:10:02.820
That was the first reason
that made me sit down.

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:05.056
And I had basically two choices.

00:10:05.056 --> 00:10:08.760
Harper-Collins told me that I
either could write it myself,

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:11.350
or have a ghostwriter.

00:10:11.350 --> 00:10:14.460
I sent the first chapter
to a ghost writer,

00:10:14.460 --> 00:10:16.580
especially because I
was going to the UK,

00:10:16.580 --> 00:10:19.580
to London, to
portray [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:23.370
in a play that was going to take
4 and 1/2 months of my life.

00:10:23.370 --> 00:10:25.090
And I thought, I'm
a method actor.

00:10:25.090 --> 00:10:29.900
I would rather not
combine works together.

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:32.830
But when the chapter
got back to me,

00:10:32.830 --> 00:10:39.920
it was beautifully written,
so rich, literally speaking.

00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:42.170
But it wasn't my voice.

00:10:42.170 --> 00:10:45.510
It sounded non-Iranian.

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:49.550
It sounded American, and
it had lost my voice.

00:10:49.550 --> 00:10:53.570
So I called back, and I
begged Harper and Collins

00:10:53.570 --> 00:10:56.650
to allow me to write it myself.

00:10:56.650 --> 00:11:00.250
And to cut the story short,
it took me 2 and 1/2 years

00:11:00.250 --> 00:11:01.000
to finish it.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:02.250
But I'm glad I did it.

00:11:02.250 --> 00:11:04.080
It has an accent, but
it doesn't matter.

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:05.510
It has my accent.

00:11:05.510 --> 00:11:10.040
So when you read it, you realize
that whatever I'm saying,

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:11.590
it's me saying it.

00:11:11.590 --> 00:11:15.110
No one has tried to add anything
to it, or take away from it,

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:16.901
or interfere with it.

00:11:16.901 --> 00:11:18.275
FEMALE SPEAKER:
So I was curious,

00:11:18.275 --> 00:11:20.770
"The Alley of Love
and Yellow Jasmines,"

00:11:20.770 --> 00:11:23.890
how did you come up that title?

00:11:23.890 --> 00:11:28.220
SHOHREH AGHDASHLOO: This is one
of my favorite, favorite things

00:11:28.220 --> 00:11:29.780
ever.

00:11:29.780 --> 00:11:35.750
As you all know, I was on "24."
"24" is amazingly successful

00:11:35.750 --> 00:11:37.500
all over the world.

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:42.710
People of the world love "24."

00:11:42.710 --> 00:11:46.450
Marrakesh, Tunisia,
Jordan, wherever

00:11:46.450 --> 00:11:49.420
I went, as soon as I open
my mouth, they were like,

00:11:49.420 --> 00:11:52.070
are you the woman on "24"?

00:11:52.070 --> 00:11:56.410
I was at the bazaar in
Marrakesh, poverty personified.

00:11:56.410 --> 00:12:00.260
This young, 10, 12 years
old boy is following me,

00:12:00.260 --> 00:12:01.940
and I was a bit afraid.

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:04.330
I noticed he's following me.

00:12:04.330 --> 00:12:07.680
I decided to act strong.

00:12:07.680 --> 00:12:09.980
I turned around, and I
looked at him, and I said,

00:12:09.980 --> 00:12:11.830
what do you want?

00:12:11.830 --> 00:12:18.550
He took a look at me, and he
said, madame, c'est artiste?

00:12:18.550 --> 00:12:20.480
I said, yes, oui.

00:12:20.480 --> 00:12:22.640
He goes, vingt-quatre?

00:12:22.640 --> 00:12:23.970
"24"?

00:12:23.970 --> 00:12:25.941
I said, what is your name?

00:12:25.941 --> 00:12:26.690
He said, Muhammad.

00:12:26.690 --> 00:12:29.160
I said, Muhammad, I
get you a sandwich.

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:30.250
I give you a coin.

00:12:30.250 --> 00:12:31.230
Do you like coca-cola?

00:12:31.230 --> 00:12:32.920
He goes, yes, I like coca-cola.

00:12:32.920 --> 00:12:35.610
Don't tell anyone
I am from "24,"

00:12:35.610 --> 00:12:39.350
or I won't be able
to leave the bazaar.

00:12:39.350 --> 00:12:42.250
In Japan, they love it.

00:12:42.250 --> 00:12:45.720
They love it in Japan,
and they dub it in Japan.

00:12:45.720 --> 00:12:48.880
So I was told that not
only one or two reporters

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:52.180
want to interview me
for "24" from Japan,

00:12:52.180 --> 00:12:54.530
but also there is
a dozen of them.

00:12:54.530 --> 00:12:59.720
Therefore, they decided to
have a moderator in LA with me,

00:12:59.720 --> 00:13:03.490
and have all these reporters
on a conference line

00:13:03.490 --> 00:13:05.188
from all over Japan.

